The CDs were synthesized according to the method reported by Liu’s group, in which chitosan was used as carbon source under microwave irradiation with a yield of 35% (Scheme 1
                        ). TEM image (Fig. 1
                        ) shows that the average size of chitosan CDs was 9.6nm.

The catalytic activities of Rh/CDs nanoparticles were also compared with other common catalysts. During the contrast experiments, hydrazine hydrate and ascorbic acid were used as reducing agent to prepare Rh nanoparticles and the resulting catalysts were compared with Rh-CD-2 (as shown in Table 3
                        ). The size and morphology of the Rh nanoparticles were examined by TEM images. As shown in Fig. S6, Rh-CD-b and Rh-CD-2 formed clusters while Rh-CD-a appeared aggregation. The clusters in Rh-CD-2 were smaller than that in Rh-CD-b, thus Rh-CD-2 may have higher specific surface area. The element compositions of the series of catalysts were analysed by EDS. As shown in Table S3, Rh-CD-b and Rh-CD-2 had similar Rh contents that were higher than that of Rh-CD-a. Fig. 8
                         shows the results of hydrogenation reaction. Rh-CD-2 exhibited higher hydrogenation activity than other catalysts due to its higher specific surface area and richer Rh content.
